  "Asparagus|Bee's Knees": "Empress Indigo gin, lemon, honey lavender syrup — three ingredients, no filler. The honey-lavender plays against asparagus's vegetal char and the lemon cuts the sulfur edge. Works as gin cocktail for asparagus — floral-and-bright route; wines peak higher on the wine-tricky vegetable.",
  "Asparagus|Bowdie's Old Fashioned": "Buffalo Trace Old Fashioned against asparagus — bourbon vanilla-caramel has no hook into a sulfur-forward vegetable side. Never layer. Route the cocktail to fatted steaks or marrow; take asparagus with Sauvignon Blanc, Sancerre, or Chablis.",
  "Asparagus|Caymus Cabernet Sauvignon": "Napa Rutherford Cab against asparagus — concentrated cocoa-mocha body is the wrong axis for a sulfur-forward vegetable. Tannin-meets-sulfur is a textbook clash. Never pair. Route Caymus to the steak course and take asparagus with Sauvignon Blanc, Sancerre, or Chablis.",
  "Asparagus|Cucumber Gimlet": "Asparagus: this light, green vegetable's clean herbal edge meets this gin cocktail's citrus brightness and botanical lift. Bright cocktail lifts light greens — both stay clean. Works cleanly.",
  "Asparagus|Domaine de Berthiers Pouilly-Fumé": "Asparagus: this light, green vegetable's clean herbal edge meets this crisp white's citrus-driven acidity and mineral edge. Bright acidity lifts green vegetables; mineral lines up with the clean vegetable bite. A vegetable-side headliner.",
  "Asparagus|Elk Cove Pinot Blanc": "Asparagus: this light, green vegetable's clean herbal edge meets this crisp white's citrus-driven acidity and mineral edge. Bright acidity lifts green vegetables; mineral lines up with the clean vegetable bite. Strong — refreshing and clean.",
  "Asparagus|Jean-Pierre Grossot Chablis": "Asparagus: this light, green vegetable's clean herbal edge meets this crisp white's citrus-driven acidity and mineral edge. Bright acidity lifts green vegetables; mineral lines up with the clean vegetable bite. A vegetable-side headliner.",
  "Asparagus|Joseph Mellot Sancerre": "Asparagus: this light, green vegetable's clean herbal edge meets this crisp white's citrus-driven acidity and mineral edge. Bright acidity lifts green vegetables; mineral lines up with the clean vegetable bite. A vegetable-side headliner.",
  "Asparagus|Laurent Perrier Le Cuvée Brut": "Tours-sur-Marne Chardonnay-blend Champagne — precise green apple, lemon zest, whisper of brioche, vibrant acidity. The high-acid finish cuts through asparagus's sulfur edge and the brioche plays against the vegetal char. Works as Champagne for asparagus — bubbles on the wine-tricky vegetable; Sauv Blancs and Sancerre peak higher on sulfur notes.",
  "Asparagus|Le Garenne Rosé": "Loire Pinot Noir rosé — delicate fresh-fruit, strawberry, crisp. The crisp body handles asparagus's sulfur notes and the fresh fruit plays against the vegetal char. Strong Loire rosé for asparagus — summer pairing on the wine-tricky vegetable.",
  "Asparagus|Lingua Franca Avni Pinot Noir": "Willamette Pinot — dark cherry, forest floor, refined structure, low tannin. The low-tannin silk lifts asparagus's tender spears and the forest-floor earth plays against the vegetal char — the rare red that handles asparagus without clashing. Strong Oregon Pinot for asparagus — unconventional but real on the wine-tricky vegetable.",
  "Asparagus|Opus One": "Oakville Bordeaux blend against asparagus — firm-tannin prestige Cab against sulfur-forward vegetable is textbook clash territory. Never pair. Route Opus to the Tomahawk or Porterhouse; take asparagus with Sauvignon Blanc, Sancerre, or Chablis.",
  "Asparagus|Raventós Cava de NIT Rosé Brut": "Asparagus: this light, green vegetable's clean herbal edge meets this sparkling rosé's strawberry-and-brioche charm with crisp acidity. Sparkling acidity mirrors the vegetable's herbal brightness. Works cleanly.",
  "Asparagus|Scavino Barolo": "Piedmont Barolo's tar-and-tannin intensity against asparagus — firm-tannin Nebbiolo on sulfur-forward vegetable is textbook clash. Never pair. Route Scavino to the Tomahawk or Porterhouse; take asparagus with Sauvignon Blanc, Sancerre, or Chablis.",
  "Asparagus|Shafer Hillside Select": "Stags Leap collector's Cab against asparagus — dense Hillside Select structure against sulfur-forward vegetable is wildly wrong. Never pair. Route Shafer to the best steak cuts; take asparagus with Sauvignon Blanc, Sancerre, or Chablis.",
